Commoditas has generally been wrongly explained, as isit meant “ advantage, benefit,'' or again, “complaisance, agreeableness.'’ The word is used in these senses in the plural by Ter. (Phorm. 841 ; Andr. 569); but in Plautus it is only used in sing, and always means ‘⁴ conve· nience, opportuneness‚'’ as above, 1134. Here commoditas is used in reference to the “ opportune appearance '' of the lllz‘les. In Men. i. 2. 31 Men. says non potuisti magis per tempus mz' aduenire quam aduenis, to which Pe. replies‚ ita ego soleo: commoditatis (z εὐκαιρίας) omnis articulos scz'0; such, also, is the usage of commoditatem in Poen. iv. 2. 94. In Men. i. 2. 28 o mea commoditas, 0 mea opportunitas salue, we have a good instance of the proper meaning of this word in Pl.
